observations.recommendation:
We have recommended and Management agreed on the following:

The Municipal Engineer stop the practice of allocating certain amount for overhead expenses as the same cannot be used for other purposes such as administrative expenses;


Management improve implementation of the DF by considering the number of implemented projects in the previous year as the basis for determining the projects to be implemented during the current year and henceforth, focus on high-impact projects; 


The Municipal Budget Officer reconcile the submitted CY 2021 and CY 2022 Continuing Appropriations and explain the noted deficiencies; and



The Municipal Engineer submit the Utilization of the DF on a quarterly basis with the complete and relevant information contained therein.

We recommended and Management agreed on the following:
The Supply Officer/Inventory Committee prepare a consolidated Inventory Report to facilitate reconciliation with the accounting records on a per account name basis and thereafter, reconcile with the accounting records to address the causes of variances;
The Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Property Unit and Accounting Office, prepare the PIP, List of PPEs found at station, and henceforth, strictly comply with COA Circular No. 2020-006 to come up with the reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts presented in the financial statements;
The Supply Officer ensure that all issuances of PPEs are covered with Property Acknowledgment Receipt (PAR), renew/update PARs every three years after issuance or whenever there is a change in custodianship and prepare IIRUP for all unserviceable PPEs and facilitate disposal thereof; and
The Municipal Accountant record adjustments after reconciliation to establish the correct balances of PPE and other affected accounts.

The Municipal Budget Officer thoroughly review and make certain that the List of Continuing Appropriations is free from errors as this will affect the percentage of completion/non-completion;
The Municipal Engineer submit the Utilization of the DF on a quarterly basis with the complete and relevant information contained therein. This is particularly significant during year-end as basis for completed projects but not yet paid in order to accurately show the percentage of completion;
The Municipal Budget Officer justify the exclusion of some items in the List of Continuing Appropriations and disbursement of three projects not found therein and in the regular/supplemental budgets;
The Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Budget Officer evaluate if there are still corrections to the computed excess fund available for appropriation, make the necessary adjustments, and recommend for re-appropriation; and
All concerned officials strictly monitor and constantly evaluate the status of implementation or utilization of the said fund and ensure timely completion or implementation of development projects.

We recommended and Management agreed on the following:
Management only divide a project in several phases if the criteria of usability is met in accordance with Section 54.1 of the RIRR of RA No. 9184;
The Municipal Engineer allocate a specified amount for signboards pursuant to COA Circular No. 2013-004. Furthermore, he should ensure that the project titles are accurate and consistent with the items of work;
The Project Engineers prepare the As-Built Plans for each project and only after the completion of work in order to show the actual work done. Moreover, these plans should sufficiently delineate the completed and uncompleted portion of the project;
The Project Engineers take pictures on the same angle before, during and after implementation with the project title written on each photo. Close-up shots should be required on embedded items while long shots be taken on the completed project to reasonably show the actual accomplishment;
The Bids and Awards Committee judiciously review and evaluate the RFQs and other documents before awarding the contract;
Demand the refund of the overpayment of services amounting to P13,200.00;
The Municipal Treasurer ascertain that invoices and receipts are duly filled out with the complete information before issuance of the checks; and
The Municipal Accountant scrutinize the disbursement vouchers and their supporting documents to ensure their propriety and completeness before affixing her signature.

Give a stern warning to the Project Engineer to conduct proper supervision and strictly monitor project implementation in accordance with plans and specifications;
Require the Engineering Office to adhere strictly to the provisions of existing DPWH Standards and Estimating Guidelines in the preparation of the ABC to avoid excessive contract costs; and
Submit justification why the contract cost is unreasonably higher than the COA Evaluated Cost; otherwise, a Notice of Disallowance will be issued;
We further recommended the following:
Justify the awarding of the project to Luwang Construction for the Construction/Opening of Sumadel Road despite lack of Safety Officer. Otherwise, require the contractor to refund the amount of P 45,000.00
On the Construction of Multipurpose Building:
Require the contractor concerned to implement corrective measures rectifying the noted deficiencies to prevent further damage to the structure, wastage of government funds and resources and avoid compromising public safety. In case the contractor fails to institute the necessary corrective actions, implement the remedies provided in Section 62 of the IRR of RA No. 9184 on warranty;
Submit the Quality Test Report, if test was made. If not, test should be conducted to ensure structural integrity of the finished structure. Likewise, documents supporting Suspension Order No. 3 should be submitted for verification; and
Deduct the excessive cost of P861,648.37 for the Construction of Multipurpose Building from succeeding claims or any amount due the contractor and/or deduct from retention money or other securities posted by the contractor, whichever is applicable; and
Submit documents to support the changes in the thickness of the CHB used for the Improvement/Upgrading of Tinglayan RHU. Otherwise, the disbursement shall be disallowed in audit.

The Accounting and Treasury Office continue to withhold and strictly remit to the BIR the correct amount of taxes to continuously provide additional income to the government;
The Municipal Accountant further analyze the taxes withheld and remitted to determine the nature and cause of the unremitted balance and likewise conduct regular review and proper monitoring of the Due to BIR account to ensure its accuracy; and
Management strictly comply with RMC No. 23-2007 and Title X of the NIRC; otherwise, the responsible officials shall be held liable for the payment of such penalties, interests and surcharges.
The Human Resource Officer (HRO) ensure timely submission of updated information of employees to the GSIS such as new salary rate, employment status, positions and such other pertinent information that will take effect in the particular due month to minimize the occurrence of unmatched records;
The HRO promptly resolve discrepancies or unmatched records between the ERF and EBF before the following month’s remittance to avoid further incurrence of penalties, interest and surcharges;
The Municipal Accountant maintain schedules for balances which remain unremitted at the end of the year and the reason for such and make appropriate disclosures in the Notes to the Financial Statement or in case of discrepancies in the account balance, effect appropriate adjustments to the account to correct the balance per books; and
Management strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 8291 and it’s implementing rules and regulations.
To come up with appropriate measures to facilitate prompt and accurate remittances to prevent recurrence of under remittances of the amount due;
The Municipal Accountant maintain schedules for balances which remain unremitted at the end of the year and the reason for such and make appropriate disclosures in the Notes to the Financial Statement; and
Concerned employees exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties and to strictly implement the rules and regulations governing the collection and full remittance of premium contributions within the prescribed period to the PHIC. Otherwise, they shall be held liable for any interest and surcharges that may be imposed.
Employ measures to facilitate prompt and accurate remittances to prevent recurrence of under remittances of the amount due;
The Municipal Accountant maintain schedules for balances which remain unremitted at the end of the year and the reason for such and make appropriate disclosures in the Notes to the Financial Statement; and
Concerned employees exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties and to strictly implement the rules and regulations governing the collection and full remittance of premium contributions and loan amortizations to the HDMF within the prescribed period. Otherwise, they shall be held liable for any interest and surcharges that may be imposed.

3.6. We have recommended and Management agreed on the following:

The Municipal Engineer stop the practice of allocating certain amount for overhead expenses as the same cannot be used for other purposes such as administrative expenses;
Management improve implementation of the DF by considering the number of implemented projects in the previous year as the basis for determining the projects to be implemented during the current year and henceforth, focus on high-impact projects;
The Municipal Budget Officer reconcile the submitted CY 2021 and CY 2022 Continuing Appropriations and explain the noted deficiencies; and
The Municipal Engineer submit the Utilization of the DF on a quarterly basis with the complete and relevant information contained therein.

4.4. We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
strictly evaluate the existence and propriety of all documentary requirements before certifying in the disbursement vouchers as to completeness of supporting documents; and
reconstruct the Repair History of all motor vehicles and attach said document on succeeding disbursements for repair. The document should present the reference (JEV/Check No.), date repair was made, amount paid, running balance, the nature of repair and the spare parts procured;
4.5. We also recommended and Management agreed on the following:
The Municipal Treasurer to accept official receipts or invoices which are completely filled out by suppliers and contractors before issuing the check; otherwise, disallowance shall be made after confirmation, if warranted;
The Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to check the sufficiency of the description of the procurement project and require that ABC be indicated in the RFQ to aid the bidder in accurately making its bid. In addition, the propriety and completeness of documents should be carefully evaluated before awarding of contracts to the winning bidder;
Management to formulate policy guidelines regarding the support to national agencies specifying the monthly allocation and the duties and responsibilities expected to be rendered as basis for evaluating their accomplishment reports;
Department Heads to review all supporting documents attached and require that deficiencies or errors be regularized or corrected before certifying in the Obligation Request as to the validity, propriety and legality of transactions to prevent suspensions and disallowances; and
Management is encouraged to strengthen internal controls in order to prevent violations of pertinent provisions of RA No. 3019, Revised Penal Code and RA No. 9184 particularly on evident bad faith and gross negligence in the performance of official functions, Falsification and Estafa, Splitting of contracts, and other violations.

7.8. We recommended and Management agreed to:
optimize the utilization of the LDRRMF and Mitigation Fund to lessen the socio-economic and environmental impacts of disasters in the community and disaster risks and to enhance disaster preparedness;
review and revise the LDRRMFIP to include the PPAs from unexpended balances from prior years using the prescribed format in COA Circular No. 2012-002 and submit the same to the OCD, DBM and DILG;
transfer the unutilized balances to the Trust Fund books at the end of the year to fully comply with the requirement of COA Circular No. 2012-002; and
prepare the RSUDRRMF on a monthly basis and show proof of submission to the OCD, DBM and DILG.

15.9. We recommended and Management agreed on the following:
Management to formulate policy guidelines in assessing the necessity of hiring job order employees taking into consideration the reasonable number needed by the different offices and the validity of work to be assigned;
The HRMA to require from the office where the job order is to be assigned a list of duties and responsibilities before deployment. These may be contained in the Assignment/Deployment Order;
The Municipal Accountant to require that all job order contracts and Assignment Order be attached in the disbursement vouchers not only in the first payment of wages. Alternatively, the HRMA may submit hardcopies of the contracts and assignment order together with the master list of job orders indicating all the necessary and relevant information thereon to the Audit Team so that succeeding payments may not be attached with such in order to save on resources; and
Management to comply with the daily minimum wage rate prescribed by the RTWPB-CAR as a model in enforcing labor rules and regulations.

